Prolog
“I beg you!” pleaded Queen Eirwen, “do not send her away! She is still a child!” The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. The thought of it darkened his gaze.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. A girl in the eyes of the Ice King meant weakness. After all, he had only sired sons up to this point.
“You have two choices: either you kill the child or you send her into the wilderness. This is her punishment for your failure, Eirwen.” He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did that.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Previously, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, while in the South was a kingdom full of fantastical powers. But the North showed its greed, and a never-ending war broke out between the two kingdoms, until the South finally offered a truce.
The despair in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the North, where she would bear a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South to form a single kingdom. The North accepted the proposal and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
“I beg you, my king, do with me as you wish, imprison me, banish me, or kill me, but spare my child,” pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his queen with utter contempt. Perhaps, but only perhaps, would he show her mercy. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his darkest times and who had given him his sons.
“Well then. The child can stay in the palace,” he said, which the queen acknowledged with a sigh. “But,” he added, “you will be executed.”
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen exchanged horrified glances. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the floor. “Yes, my king.” She bowed her head.
The Ice King ordered his royal advisor to bring the Queen's daughter into one of Eirwen's free rooms. Afterwards, he ordered the guards to take Eirwen to the execution square, where all the citizens of the city could watch.
As the guards escorted her to the execution square, there was a loud uproar among the citizens when they realized that their only, beloved queen was to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards. Others questioned why this should happen, but all were in agreement.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The executioner. The woman, who had just been a queen, was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the worst thing one could do to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The residents of Frostfell refused to believe the king and did not accept his words. Then the executioner lit the wooden stake on fire, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Don't give up, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Deathly silence in the palace
Only a knock was heard from the room located farthest to the left in the perpetually cold palace's southern wing. The servants, who came by, wondered what was inside the room. They were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors among the servants spread. It was supposedly said that the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room and was waiting to be let out.
Her assumption could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory and walked towards the southern wing, while the servants wandered around and whispered to each other. They had no idea what was hidden behind the door.
The rumors naturally also concerned Ivory, since Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Klopf, klopf. „Lady Kari, are you in there?“, whispered Ivory before the door, intricately decorated with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if – unlike the last attempt – entry would actually be granted. I still have blue bruises from the last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book at Ivory's shoulder, but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock was heard from inside, probably to indicate that she was there. Where else would she be?
„May I enter?“, asked Ivory. Earlier, Ivory would have entered without asking.
Aus dem Inneren vernahm Ivory ein Klopfen. Das bedeutete wohl ein „Ja“. Die Kälte und das Geräusch ließen Ivory erschauern. Es fühlte sich komisch an, ein Geräusch aus einem angeblich leeren Zimmer zu hören, obwohl Ivory schon seit einigen Jahren dort hineinging.
„Ich komme rein“, sagte Ivory und öffnete langsam die Tür. Der Anblick, der sich Ivory in dem Raum bot, war für normale Menschen ungewöhnlich, kam für Ivory aber nicht unerwartet. Überall lag Papier. Bücher waren verstreut, der Schreibtisch war zerbrochen und mehrere Eisskulpturen lagen herum. Es gab keine Fenster und wenig bis gar kein Licht. Außerdem war es kälter als im restlichen Palast (was schon einiges sagte). Der Raum sah aus, als sei ein Schneesturm hindurch gefegt.
Das Mädchen lag zusammengerollt in ihrem Bett, eingewickelt in ihre Bettdecke, und las in einem ihrer Notizbücher. Eine kleine Laterne erhellte den Raum.
„Welches Notizbuch ist das?“, fragte Ivory und setzte sich neben Kari aufs Bett.
